05326nam a22006855i 9780814749234DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19971997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147492347 a10.18574/nyu/9780814749234.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)546872  a(OCoLC)45844047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMED0220002bisacsh04a362.19698  aLC 560002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90662:7721 aKroll-Smith, Steve, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBodies in Protest :bEnvironmental Illness and the Struggle Over Medical Knowledge /cSteve Kroll-Smith, H. Hugh Floyd. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart One -- t1. Environmental Illness as a Practical Epistemology and a Source of Professional Confusion -- t2. Chemically Reactive Bodies, Knowledge, and Society -- tPart Two -- t3. Something Unusual Is Happening Here -- t4. Bodies against Theory -- t5. Explaining Strange Bodies -- tPart Three -- t6. Representation and the Political Economy of a New Body -- t7. A New Body in the Courts, Federal Policies, the Market, and Beyond -- tConclusion -- t8. Bodies, Environments, and Interpretive Space -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGulf War Syndrome: Is It a Real Disease? asks a recent headline in the New York Times. This question—are certain diseases real?—lies at the heart of a simmering controversy in the United States, a debate that has raged, in different contexts, for centuries. In the early nineteenth century, the air of European cities, polluted by open sewers and industrial waste, was generally thought to be the source of infection and disease. Thus the term miasma—literally deathlike air—came into popular use, only to be later dismissed as medically unsound by Louis Pasteur. While controversy has long swirled in the United States around such illnesses as chronic fatigue syndrome and Epstein-Barr virus, no disorder has been more aggressively contested than environmental illness, a disease whose symptoms are distinguished by an extreme, debilitating reaction to a seemingly ordinary environment. The environmentally ill range from those who have adverse reactions to strong perfumes or colognes to others who are so sensitive to chemicals of any kind that they must retreat entirely from the modern world. Bodies in Protest does not seek to answer the question of whether or not chemical sensitivity is physiological or psychological, rather, it reveals how ordinary people borrow the expert language of medicine to construct lay accounts of their misery. The environmentally ill are not only explaining their bodies to themselves, however, they are also influencing public policies and laws to accommodate the existence of these mysterious illnesses. They have created literally a new body that professional medicine refuses to acknowledge and one that is becoming a popular model for rethinking conventional boundaries between the safe and the dangerous. Having interviewed dozens of the environmentally ill, the authors here recount how these people come to acknowledge and define their disease, and themselves, in a suddenly unlivable world that often stigmatizes them as psychologically unstable. Bodies in Protest is the dramatic story of human bodies that no longer behave in a manner modern medicine can predict and control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAllergy. 0aEnvironmentally induced diseases. 7aMEDICAL / Diseases.2bisacsh1 aFloyd, H. Hugh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary